---
import Layout from '../layouts/Layout.astro';
import AboutAvatar from '../components/AboutAvatar.astro';
---

<Layout
	title="About | oomkill.dev"
	description="About oomkill.dev: a personal notebook for systems topics, experiments, and things worth remembering."
>
	<div class="about-page" data-about-page>
		<header class="about-hero">
			<div class="about-hero-text">
				<p class="about-eyebrow">About</p>
				<h1 class="about-title">A notebook for things I find interesting.</h1>
				<p class="about-lead">
					I'm Aryan Narayan. I write here when I learn something about systems, networking, or infrastructure
					that I want to keep, usually after reading docs, breaking a toy setup, or running a small
					experiment on my own machine.
				</p>
			</div>
			<div class="about-hero-figure">
				<AboutAvatar />
			</div>
		</header>

		<section class="about-body">
			<div class="about-block">
				<h2 class="about-heading">What this site is</h2>
				<p>
					<strong>oomkill.dev</strong> is my personal notebook. I write here when I want a concept to stick: not
					a fleeting bookmark, but something I can come back to in a month or a year and still understand.
				</p>
				<p>
					Most posts start as notes I'd otherwise lose: a diagram, a command that finally made sense, a small
					experiment that proved a point. I polish them enough that they're worth keeping, ideally for a long
					time. Maybe forever. That's the bar.
				</p>
			</div>

			<div class="about-block">
				<h2 class="about-heading">What I write about</h2>
				<p>
					Linux, networking, HTTP, Kubernetes, observability, performance: whatever I'm digging into at the
					moment. If I can reproduce it in a lab or a small demo, it might end up as a post.
				</p>
			</div>

			<div class="about-topics" aria-label="Topics">
				<span class="about-chip">systems</span>
				<span class="about-chip">networking</span>
				<span class="about-chip">linux</span>
				<span class="about-chip">experiments</span>
				<span class="about-chip">kubernetes</span>
			</div>

			<div class="about-block">
				<h2 class="about-heading">Why oomkill</h2>
				<p>
					The Linux OOM killer shows up when memory runs out and something has to die. It's brutal and kind of
					funny, and a reminder that resources are finite and abstractions leak. This site is named after that.
					Here it's only words. Hopefully.
				</p>
			</div>

			<p class="about-footer-note">
				Want to follow along? Read the <a href="/blog">writing</a> or grab the
				<a href="/rss.xml">RSS feed</a>.
			</p>
		</section>
	</div>
</Layout>
